04270nam a22005775i 9780822395782DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20122012ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223957827 a10.1515/97808223957822doi  a(DE-B1597)554250  a(OCoLC)1202625805  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aRA448.5.N4bP65 2012 7aMED0100002bisacsh04a616.1/20089960732231 aPollock, Anne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMedicating Race :bHeart Disease and Durable Preoccupations with Difference /cAnne Pollock. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b5 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aExperimental futures : technological lives, scientific arts, anthropological voices00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Racial Preoccupations and Early Cardiology -- t2. Making Normal Populations and Making Difference in the Framingham and Jackson Heart Studies -- t3. The Durability of African American Hypertension as a Disease Category -- t4. The Slavery Hypothesis beyond Genetic Determinism -- t5. Thiazide Diuretics at a Nexus of Associations: Racialized, Proven, Old, Cheap -- t6. BiDil: Medicating the Intersection of Race and Heart Failure -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Medicating Race, Anne Pollock traces the intersecting discourses of race, pharmaceuticals, and heart disease in the United States over the past century, from the founding of cardiology through the FDA's approval of BiDil, the first drug sanctioned for use in a specific race. She examines wide-ranging aspects of the dynamic interplay of race and heart disease: articulations, among the founders of American cardiology, of heart disease as a modern, and therefore white, illness; constructions of "normal" populations in epidemiological research, including the influential Framingham Heart Study; debates about the distinctiveness African American hypertension, which turn on disparate yet intersecting arguments about genetic legacies of slavery and the comparative efficacy of generic drugs; and physician advocacy for the urgent needs of black patients on professional, scientific, and social justice grounds. Ultimately, Pollock insists that those grappling with the meaning of racialized medical technologies must consider not only the troubled history of race and biomedicine but also its fraught yet vital present. Medical treatment should be seen as a site of, rather than an alternative to, political and social contestation. The aim of scholarly analysis should not be to settle matters of race and genetics, but to hold medicine more broadly accountable to truth and justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aAfrican AmericansxHealth and hygiene. 0aAfrican AmericansxMedical care. 0aCardiologyzUnited States. 0aHeartxDiseaseszUnited States. 7aMEDICAL / Cardiology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822395782zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822395782423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822395782.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles